definition.value: Poly(A)-position profiling by sequencing (3P-Seq)
3’-end sequencing for expression quantification (3SEQ) from FFPE samples
Gene-specific differences in elongation rates in vivo (4sUDRB-seq)
Detect nascent RNA with a 5’ 7-methylguanylated cap (5’-GRO-seq)
Profiles the genome-wide abundance of mRNA degradation intermediates by their 5′-phosphorylated ends (5PSeq)
AbaSI coupled with sequencing (Aba-seq)
Advanced or long read ChIA-PET uses Tn5 transposases
Map miRNA binding to AGO sites in C. elegans
Automated high-throughput ChIP-seq (AHT-ChIP-seq)
Autonomously replicating sequence assay (ARS-seq)
Multiplexed barcode sequencing (Bar-seq)
Characterize phenotypes of hundreds of different AAV strains
Bisulfite-treated chromatin immuno-precipitated DNA (BisChIP-seq), to correlate protein modifications with DNA methylation
Breaks labeling, enrichment on streptavidin and sequencing (BLESS)
iCLIP with BrdU affinity purification (BrdU-CLIP)
Double-stranded break labeling to map chromosome breaks (Break-seq)
5’-Bromo-uridine immunoprecipitation chase (BRIC-Seq)
Bromouridine labeling and sequencing (Bru-seq) is a method for probing RNA synthesis by pulling down bromouridine residues in nascent transcripts followed by sequencing.
Bromouridine pulse-chase and sequencing (BruChase-Seq)
BruDRB-seq— to reveal gene-specific differences in elongation rates
an approach that complements the Bru-seq technique by enhancing nascent RNA signal around promoters and enhancers genome-wide in intact cells
Bisulfite conversion of genomic DNA (bs-Seq)
Bisulfite amplicon sequencing (BSAS)
Bisulfite sequencing with padlock probes (BSPP)
Chemical modification-assisted bisulfite sequencing (CAB-Seq) for 5caC detection
CAGEscan: a mate-pair adaptation of nanoCAGE that captures the transcript 5′ ends linked to a downstream region
5caC methylase-assisted bisulfite sequencing (caMAB-seq)
CXXC affinity purification plus deep sequencing (CAP-seq)
Cancer personalized profiling by deep sequencing (CAPP-Seq)
5’ anchored profiling of Pol II transcripts (CapSeq). Identifies pre-mRNAs, transspliced mRNAs, miRNAs, and noncoding RNAs

Capture Hi-C is a type of Hi-C assay in which a selection step is performed on ligated fragments in order to select for ligation products containing specific regions, often used to enrich for promoter regions.
RNA capture sequencing (CaptureSeq)
Chromatin affinity purification from specific cell types by chromatin immunoprecipitation (CAST-ChIP)
Covalent attachment of tags to capture histones (CATCH‑IT)
Capture of Associated Targets on CHromatin (CATCH)
Cell expression by linear amplification and sequencing (CEL-Seq).
Chromatin affinity precipitation (ChAP)-seq
Capture hybridization analysis of RNA targets (CHART)
Chromatin endogenous cleavage
Chem-seq: to identify the sites bound by small chemical molecules

ChIA-PET (chromatin interaction analysis by paired-end tag sequencing) is a type of chromosome conformation capture assay that uses chromatin immunoprecipitation to enrich for protein-specific chromatin complexes after digestion, followed by nuclear proximity ligation and high-throughput paired-end-tag sequencing.
Bisulfite-treated chromatin immunoprecipitated DNA (ChIP-BS-seq), to correlate protein modifications with DNA methylation
Fast, robust, low-input ChIP-seq for histones and transcription factors
Chromatin Isolation by RNA Purification (ChIRP)
CIP-TAP for identifying capped small RNA (csRNA) species
Extrachromosomal circular DNA sequencing (Circle-Seq)
Chemical inference of RNA structures (CIRS-seq)
Identify low abundance RNA viruses with circular sequencing (CirSeq)
Cell labeling via photobleaching (CLaP)
Crosslinking, ligation, and sequencing of hybrids (CLASH)
